                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 Stam, John C./30: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-17T20:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 17, 1935—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 17—12:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. Reference Nanking’s No. 6 of January 17, noon, concerning Stam case. The
                    following telegram has been sent to Peck.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“January 17, 8 p.m. Your January 17, noon. The Legation is skeptical of truth
                        of this report, and will be interested to examine <pb facs="0780" n="668"
                            xml:id="pg_668"/> whatever proof may be offered by the Foreign Office to
                        support it. Please avoid making any statement at the Foreign Office
                        suggestive of acceptance of or satisfaction with any such report or
                        statement.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
